{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01LF5NjQEzw5Bbatut6LXrZo","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tname: paper-writer\n3\tdescription: Write academic papers from experiment results using LaTeX. Use when experiments are complete and REPORT.md exists, when asked to write a paper, or when generating publication-ready documents in NeurIPS style.\n4\t---\n5\t\n6\t# Paper Writer\n7\t\n8\tGuide for writing academic papers from experiment results using a two-stage process.\n9\t\n10\t## When to Use\n11\t\n12\t- After experiments are complete and REPORT.md exists\n13\t- When explicitly asked to write a paper\n14\t- When generating publication-ready documents\n15\t\n16\t## Before Writing - Required Steps\n17\t\n18\t**IMPORTANT**: Before writing any content, you MUST complete these steps:\n19\t\n20\t1. **Read the style guide**: Review `templates/paper_writing/lab_style_guide.md` for comprehensive formatting and language conventions\n21\t\n22\t2. **Study example papers**: Browse `paper_examples/` to understand our lab's style:\n23\t   - **Language patterns**: Look at `sections/1.introduction.tex` or `sections/introduction.tex`\n24\t   - **Table formatting**: Look at `tables/*.tex` files\n25\t   - **Figure layouts**: Look at `figures/*.tex` files\n26\t   - **Macro usage**: Look at `commands/*.tex` files\n27\t\n28\t3. **Verify command templates**: Command templates are pre-copied to `paper_draft/commands/`:\n29\t   - `math.tex` - Math notation macros\n30\t   - `general.tex` - Formatting macros (`\\para{}`, colors, etc.)\n31\t   - `macros.tex` - Template for project-specific terms (customize for your paper)\n32\t\n33\t4. **CRITICAL**: Reference example papers for **FORMATTING and LANGUAGE STYLE only**\n34\t   - Do NOT copy content, phrasing, or narrative structure\n35\t   - The example papers are in different research domains\n36\t   - Focus only on HOW things are formatted, not WHAT is written\n37\t\n38\t5. **Set paper author**: Read `.neurico/idea.yaml` to find `idea.metadata.author`:\n39\t   - If `metadata.author` exists: use `<author name> and NeuriCo`\n40\t   - If no `metadata.author`: use `NeuriCo`\n41\t\n42\t## Two-Stage Writing Process\n43\t\n44\t### Stage 1: Outline Development\n45\t\n46\tBefore writing prose, create a detailed outline:\n47\t\n48\t1. **Skeleton**: Section headers and subsection structure\n49\t2. **Key points**: Bullet points for each section (3-5 per section)\n50\t3. **Evidence mapping**: Link each claim to supporting data/figures\n51\t4. **Citation placeholders**: Note where references are needed\n52\t5. **Figure/table planning**: List required visuals\n53\t\n54\tSave outline to `paper/OUTLINE.md` for review before proceeding.\n55\t\n56\t### Stage 2: Prose Writing\n57\t\n58\tConvert outline to full prose:\n59\t\n60\t1. Write section by section (don't jump around)\n61\t2. Expand each bullet into 2-4 sentences\n62\t3. Add transitions between paragraphs\n63\t4. Insert citations as you write\n64\t5. Create figures/tables as needed\n65\t\n66\t## Paper Structure (IMRAD Format)\n67\t\n68\t### 1. Title\n69\t- Clear, specific, informative\n70\t- Conveys main finding or contribution\n71\t- No acronyms unless universally known\n72\t\n73\t### 2. Abstract (150-250 words)\n74\t\n75\tFollow this structure:\n76\t- **Context/Problem** (1-2 sentences): Why does this matter?\n77\t- **Gap/Challenge** (1 sentence): What's missing?\n78\t- **Our approach** (1-2 sentences): What did we do?\n79\t- **Key results** (2-3 sentences): What did we find?\n80\t- **Significance** (1 sentence): Why does it matter?\n81\t\n82\t### 3. Introduction\n83\t\n84\tStructure:\n85\t1. **Hook** (1 paragraph): Why does this problem matter?\n86\t2. **Background** (1-2 paragraphs): What do readers need to know?\n87\t3. **Gap** (1 paragraph): What's missing in existing work?\n88\t4. **Contribution** (1 paragraph): What do we provide? Be specific with bullets:\n89\t   - Contribution 1\n90\t   - Contribution 2\n91\t   - Contribution 3\n92\t5. **Organization** (optional): Brief roadmap of paper\n93\t\n94\t### 4. Related Work\n95\t\n96\tOrganization strategies:\n97\t- **By theme**: Group papers by approach/concept\n98\t- **By timeline**: Historical development (less preferred)\n99\t- **By relationship**: How papers relate to ours\n100\t\n101\tFor each group:\n102\t- Summarize the approach\n103\t- Identify limitations\n104\t- Position our work: \"Unlike X, we...\" or \"Building on X, we...\"\n105\t\n106\t### 5. Method/Approach\n107\t\n108\tEssential elements:\n109\t- Problem formulation (formal if appropriate)\n110\t- Method description (clear enough to reproduce)\n111\t- Design justifications (why this choice?)\n112\t- Algorithm/pseudocode (if complex)\n113\t- Complexity analysis (if relevant)\n114\t\n115\t### 6. Experiments\n116\t\n117\tStructure:\n118\t1. **Setup**\n119\t   - Datasets: source, size, preprocessing\n120\t   - Baselines: what and why\n121\t   - Metrics: what and why\n122\t   - Implementation: hardware, hyperparameters\n123\t\n124\t2. **Main Results**\n125\t   - Tables with clear captions\n126\t   - Statistical significance (confidence intervals or p-values)\n127\t   - Bold best results\n128\t\n129\t3. **Analysis**\n130\t   - What do the numbers mean?\n131\t   - Why does our method work?\n132\t   - Where does it fail?\n133\t\n134\t4. **Ablations**\n135\t   - Component contributions\n136\t   - Sensitivity analysis\n137\t   - Design choice validation\n138\t\n139\t### 7. Discussion\n140\t\n141\tCover:\n142\t- Limitations (be honest and specific)\n143\t- Broader implications\n144\t- Failure cases and edge cases\n145\t- Connections to theory (if applicable)\n146\t\n147\t### 8. Conclusion\n148\t\n149\tFormat:\n150\t- Summary (1 paragraph): What did we do and find?\n151\t- Key takeaway (1 sentence): What should readers remember?\n152\t- Future work (2-3 sentences): What comes next?\n153\t\n154\t## LaTeX Template\n155\t\n156\tStyle files (.sty, .bst) are copied to the `paper_draft/` directory. The exact preamble (package name, options, bibliography style) is specified in your prompt - follow it exactly.\n157\t\n158\t### Template Structure\n159\t```latex\n160\t\\documentclass{article}\n161\t% Conference style package - USE THE EXACT LINE FROM YOUR PROMPT\n162\t\\usepackage{<style_package>}  % e.g., neurips_2025, icml2026, etc.\n163\t\n164\t% Required packages - ALWAYS include these\n165\t\\usepackage[hidelinks]{hyperref}  % Clickable links (REQUIRED)\n166\t\\usepackage{booktabs}  % Better tables (REQUIRED)\n167\t\\usepackage{graphicx}  % Figures\n168\t\\usepackage{amsmath,amssymb}  % Math\n169\t\n170\t% Import command files\n171\t\\input{commands/math}\n172\t\\input{commands/general}\n173\t\\input{commands/macros}\n174\t\n175\t\\title{Clear Title That Conveys Main Contribution}\n176\t\n177\t% Set author based on .neurico/idea.yaml metadata.author:\n178\t%   If metadata.author exists: \\author{<author name> and NeuriCo}\n179\t%   If no metadata.author:     \\author{NeuriCo}\n180\t\\author{NeuriCo}\n181\t\n182\t\\begin{document}\n183\t\\maketitle\n184\t\n185\t\\begin{abstract}\n186\tYour abstract here (150-250 words).\n187\t\\end{abstract}\n188\t\n189\t\\section{Introduction}\n190\t...\n191\t\n192\t\\bibliography{references}\n193\t\\bibliographystyle{<bib_style>}  % Use the style from your prompt\n194\t\n195\t\\end{document}\n196\t```\n197\t\n198\t### Table Formatting\n199\t\n200\t```latex\n201\t\\begin{table}[h]\n202\t\\centering\n203\t\\caption{Results comparing methods on [benchmark].\n204\t         Higher is better for all metrics.\n205\t         Best results in \\textbf{bold}.}\n206\t\\begin{tabular}{lcc}\n207\t\\toprule\n208\tMethod & Accuracy (\\%) & F1 (\\%) \\\\\n209\t\\midrule\n210\tBaseline 1 & 75.2 {\\scriptsize $\\pm$ 0.3} & 72.1 {\\scriptsize $\\pm$ 0.4} \\\\\n211\tBaseline 2 & 78.4 {\\scriptsize $\\pm$ 0.2} & 75.8 {\\scriptsize $\\pm$ 0.3} \\\\\n212\t\\midrule\n213\tOurs & \\textbf{82.1} {\\scriptsize $\\pm$ 0.2} & \\textbf{79.4} {\\scriptsize $\\pm$ 0.3} \\\\\n214\t\\bottomrule\n215\t\\end{tabular}\n216\t\\label{tab:main_results}\n217\t\\end{table}\n218\t```\n219\t\n220\t### Figure Formatting\n221\t\n222\t```latex\n223\t\\begin{figure}[h]\n224\t\\centering\n225\t\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\linewidth]{figures/main_result.pdf}\n226\t\\caption{Caption should be self-contained. Explain what is shown,\n227\t         highlight key observations, and note any important details.}\n228\t\\label{fig:main_result}\n229\t\\end{figure}\n230\t```\n231\t\n232\t## Citation Guidelines\n233\t\n234\t### BibTeX Format\n235\t\n236\t```bibtex\n237\t@inproceedings{author2024title,\n238\t  title={Full Paper Title},\n239\t  author={Last, First and Last2, First2},\n240\t  booktitle={Conference Name},\n241\t  year={2024}\n242\t}\n243\t```\n244\t\n245\t### Citation Style\n246\t\n247\t- Use `\\cite{key}` for parenthetical: \"...as shown previously (Author et al., 2024)\"\n248\t- Use `\\citet{key}` for textual: \"Author et al. (2024) showed that...\"\n249\t\n250\t## Lab Style Conventions\n251\t\n252\t### Quick Reference\n253\t\n254\tThese are the key conventions from our lab's writing style. See `templates/paper_writing/lab_style_guide.md` for complete documentation.\n255\t\n256\t**Language:**\n257\t- Active voice: \"We propose\", \"We examine\", \"We focus on\"\n258\t- Clear and simple - prefer plain language over jargon\n259\t- Bold questions as organizers: `{\\bf what is hypothesis generation?}`\n260\t- Specific quantitative claims: \"8.97% over baselines\"\n261\t\n262\t**Structure:**\n263\t- Modular `commands/` directory with `math.tex`, `general.tex`, `macros.tex`\n264\t- Import with `\\input{commands/math}` etc.\n265\t\n266\t**Macros:**\n267\t- Vectors: `\\va`, `\\vb`, ..., `\\vz` (bold lowercase)\n268\t- Matrices: `\\mA`, `\\mB`, ..., `\\mZ` (bold uppercase)\n269\t- References: `\\figref{}`, `\\Figref{}`, `\\secref{}` (not raw `\\ref{}`)\n270\t- Method names: `\\newcommand{\\methodname}{\\textsc{Name}\\xspace}`\n271\t\n272\t**Tables:**\n273\t- Always use `booktabs` (`\\toprule`, `\\midrule`, `\\bottomrule`)\n274\t- Use `\\resizebox{\\textwidth}{!}{...}` for wide tables\n275\t- Use `@{}` at edges, `\\cmidrule(lr){x-y}` for sub-headers\n276\t- Bold best results\n277\t\n278\t**Hyperlinks (Required):**\n279\t- Always use `\\usepackage[hidelinks]{hyperref}`\n280\t- All citations, refs must be clickable\n281\t\n282\t**Figures:**\n283\t- Use `0.32\\textwidth` for 3-column subfigures\n284\t- Use `\\input{figures/legend}` for shared legends\n285\t- Self-contained captions\n286\t\n287\t**Contribution Lists:**\n288\t```latex\n289\t\\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=0pt,topsep=0pt]\n290\t    \\item We propose...\n291\t    \\item We conduct...\n292\t\\end{itemize}\n293\t```\n294\t\n295\t## Output\n296\t\n297\tSave to `paper_draft/` directory with this structure:\n298\t```\n299\tpaper_draft/\n300\t├── main.tex              # Main document\n301\t├── references.bib        # BibTeX citations\n302\t├── commands/\n303\t│   ├── math.tex          # Math notation macros\n304\t│   ├── general.tex       # Formatting macros\n305\t│   └── macros.tex        # Project-specific terms\n306\t├── sections/\n307\t│   ├── abstract.tex\n308\t│   ├── introduction.tex\n309\t│   └── ...\n310\t├── figures/              # Figure files (PDF preferred)\n311\t└── tables/               # Complex standalone tables\n312\t```\n313\t\n314\tCompile with:\n315\t```bash\n316\tcd paper_draft && pdflatex main && bibtex main && pdflatex main && pdflatex main\n317\t```\n318\t\n319\t## Quality Checklist\n320\t\n321\t### Content\n322\t- [ ] Title reflects main contribution\n323\t- [ ] Abstract is self-contained (no citations, no undefined terms)\n324\t- [ ] Contributions clearly stated in introduction\n325\t- [ ] All claims supported by evidence\n326\t- [ ] Limitations honestly discussed\n327\t- [ ] Related work positions paper clearly\n328\t\n329\t### Technical\n330\t- [ ] Method reproducible from description\n331\t- [ ] All experimental details provided\n332\t- [ ] Statistical significance reported\n333\t- [ ] Ablations validate design choices\n334\t\n335\t### Presentation\n336\t- [ ] Figures have informative captions\n337\t- [ ] Tables are properly formatted\n338\t- [ ] All citations present and correct\n339\t- [ ] No placeholder text\n340\t- [ ] Consistent notation throughout\n341\t- [ ] Proofread for typos\n342\t\n343\t### Ethics\n344\t- [ ] Broader impact considered\n345\t- [ ] Potential negative uses discussed\n346\t- [ ] Data/model limitations noted\n347\t\n348\t## References\n349\t\n350\tSee `references/` folder for:\n351\t- `writing_guidelines.md`: Section-specific writing advice\n352\t\n353\tSee `assets/` folder for:\n354\t- `paper_outline_template.md`: Template for Stage 1 outline\n355\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6fbcd0a4-5ad7-4447-9fee-7a7864e1073f","uuid":"a9a943ed-ea52-4fa5-9287-9ff24703bb5c","timestamp":"2026-07-03T10:17:07.008Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspaces/predicting_lichess_chess_puzzl_20260702_184615_ee687164/.claude/skills/paper-writer/SKILL.md","content":"---\nname: paper-writer\ndescription: Write academic papers from experiment results using LaTeX. Use when experiments are complete and REPORT.md exists, when asked to write a paper, or when generating publication-ready documents in NeurIPS style.\n---\n\n# Paper Writer\n\nGuide for writing academic papers from experiment results using a two-stage process.\n\n## When to Use\n\n- After experiments are complete and REPORT.md exists\n- When explicitly asked to write a paper\n- When generating publication-ready documents\n\n## Before Writing - Required Steps\n\n**IMPORTANT**: Before writing any content, you MUST complete these steps:\n\n1. **Read the style guide**: Review `templates/paper_writing/lab_style_guide.md` for comprehensive formatting and language conventions\n\n2. **Study example papers**: Browse `paper_examples/` to understand our lab's style:\n   - **Language patterns**: Look at `sections/1.introduction.tex` or `sections/introduction.tex`\n   - **Table formatting**: Look at `tables/*.tex` files\n   - **Figure layouts**: Look at `figures/*.tex` files\n   - **Macro usage**: Look at `commands/*.tex` files\n\n3. **Verify command templates**: Command templates are pre-copied to `paper_draft/commands/`:\n   - `math.tex` - Math notation macros\n   - `general.tex` - Formatting macros (`\\para{}`, colors, etc.)\n   - `macros.tex` - Template for project-specific terms (customize for your paper)\n\n4. **CRITICAL**: Reference example papers for **FORMATTING and LANGUAGE STYLE only**\n   - Do NOT copy content, phrasing, or narrative structure\n   - The example papers are in different research domains\n   - Focus only on HOW things are formatted, not WHAT is written\n\n5. **Set paper author**: Read `.neurico/idea.yaml` to find `idea.metadata.author`:\n   - If `metadata.author` exists: use `<author name> and NeuriCo`\n   - If no `metadata.author`: use `NeuriCo`\n\n## Two-Stage Writing Process\n\n### Stage 1: Outline Development\n\nBefore writing prose, create a detailed outline:\n\n1. **Skeleton**: Section headers and subsection structure\n2. **Key points**: Bullet points for each section (3-5 per section)\n3. **Evidence mapping**: Link each claim to supporting data/figures\n4. **Citation placeholders**: Note where references are needed\n5. **Figure/table planning**: List required visuals\n\nSave outline to `paper/OUTLINE.md` for review before proceeding.\n\n### Stage 2: Prose Writing\n\nConvert outline to full prose:\n\n1. Write section by section (don't jump around)\n2. Expand each bullet into 2-4 sentences\n3. Add transitions between paragraphs\n4. Insert citations as you write\n5. Create figures/tables as needed\n\n## Paper Structure (IMRAD Format)\n\n### 1. Title\n- Clear, specific, informative\n- Conveys main finding or contribution\n- No acronyms unless universally known\n\n### 2. Abstract (150-250 words)\n\nFollow this structure:\n- **Context/Problem** (1-2 sentences): Why does this matter?\n- **Gap/Challenge** (1 sentence): What's missing?\n- **Our approach** (1-2 sentences): What did we do?\n- **Key results** (2-3 sentences): What did we find?\n- **Significance** (1 sentence): Why does it matter?\n\n### 3. Introduction\n\nStructure:\n1. **Hook** (1 paragraph): Why does this problem matter?\n2. **Background** (1-2 paragraphs): What do readers need to know?\n3. **Gap** (1 paragraph): What's missing in existing work?\n4. **Contribution** (1 paragraph): What do we provide? Be specific with bullets:\n   - Contribution 1\n   - Contribution 2\n   - Contribution 3\n5. **Organization** (optional): Brief roadmap of paper\n\n### 4. Related Work\n\nOrganization strategies:\n- **By theme**: Group papers by approach/concept\n- **By timeline**: Historical development (less preferred)\n- **By relationship**: How papers relate to ours\n\nFor each group:\n- Summarize the approach\n- Identify limitations\n- Position our work: \"Unlike X, we...\" or \"Building on X, we...\"\n\n### 5. Method/Approach\n\nEssential elements:\n- Problem formulation (formal if appropriate)\n- Method description (clear enough to reproduce)\n- Design justifications (why this choice?)\n- Algorithm/pseudocode (if complex)\n- Complexity analysis (if relevant)\n\n### 6. Experiments\n\nStructure:\n1. **Setup**\n   - Datasets: source, size, preprocessing\n   - Baselines: what and why\n   - Metrics: what and why\n   - Implementation: hardware, hyperparameters\n\n2. **Main Results**\n   - Tables with clear captions\n   - Statistical significance (confidence intervals or p-values)\n   - Bold best results\n\n3. **Analysis**\n   - What do the numbers mean?\n   - Why does our method work?\n   - Where does it fail?\n\n4. **Ablations**\n   - Component contributions\n   - Sensitivity analysis\n   - Design choice validation\n\n### 7. Discussion\n\nCover:\n- Limitations (be honest and specific)\n- Broader implications\n- Failure cases and edge cases\n- Connections to theory (if applicable)\n\n### 8. Conclusion\n\nFormat:\n- Summary (1 paragraph): What did we do and find?\n- Key takeaway (1 sentence): What should readers remember?\n- Future work (2-3 sentences): What comes next?\n\n## LaTeX Template\n\nStyle files (.sty, .bst) are copied to the `paper_draft/` directory. The exact preamble (package name, options, bibliography style) is specified in your prompt - follow it exactly.\n\n### Template Structure\n```latex\n\\documentclass{article}\n% Conference style package - USE THE EXACT LINE FROM YOUR PROMPT\n\\usepackage{<style_package>}  % e.g., neurips_2025, icml2026, etc.\n\n% Required packages - ALWAYS include these\n\\usepackage[hidelinks]{hyperref}  % Clickable links (REQUIRED)\n\\usepackage{booktabs}  % Better tables (REQUIRED)\n\\usepackage{graphicx}  % Figures\n\\usepackage{amsmath,amssymb}  % Math\n\n% Import command files\n\\input{commands/math}\n\\input{commands/general}\n\\input{commands/macros}\n\n\\title{Clear Title That Conveys Main Contribution}\n\n% Set author based on .neurico/idea.yaml metadata.author:\n%   If metadata.author exists: \\author{<author name> and NeuriCo}\n%   If no metadata.author:     \\author{NeuriCo}\n\\author{NeuriCo}\n\n\\begin{document}\n\\maketitle\n\n\\begin{abstract}\nYour abstract here (150-250 words).\n\\end{abstract}\n\n\\section{Introduction}\n...\n\n\\bibliography{references}\n\\bibliographystyle{<bib_style>}  % Use the style from your prompt\n\n\\end{document}\n```\n\n### Table Formatting\n\n```latex\n\\begin{table}[h]\n\\centering\n\\caption{Results comparing methods on [benchmark].\n         Higher is better for all metrics.\n         Best results in \\textbf{bold}.}\n\\begin{tabular}{lcc}\n\\toprule\nMethod & Accuracy (\\%) & F1 (\\%) \\\\\n\\midrule\nBaseline 1 & 75.2 {\\scriptsize $\\pm$ 0.3} & 72.1 {\\scriptsize $\\pm$ 0.4} \\\\\nBaseline 2 & 78.4 {\\scriptsize $\\pm$ 0.2} & 75.8 {\\scriptsize $\\pm$ 0.3} \\\\\n\\midrule\nOurs & \\textbf{82.1} {\\scriptsize $\\pm$ 0.2} & \\textbf{79.4} {\\scriptsize $\\pm$ 0.3} \\\\\n\\bottomrule\n\\end{tabular}\n\\label{tab:main_results}\n\\end{table}\n```\n\n### Figure Formatting\n\n```latex\n\\begin{figure}[h]\n\\centering\n\\includegraphics[width=0.8\\linewidth]{figures/main_result.pdf}\n\\caption{Caption should be self-contained. Explain what is shown,\n         highlight key observations, and note any important details.}\n\\label{fig:main_result}\n\\end{figure}\n```\n\n## Citation Guidelines\n\n### BibTeX Format\n\n```bibtex\n@inproceedings{author2024title,\n  title={Full Paper Title},\n  author={Last, First and Last2, First2},\n  booktitle={Conference Name},\n  year={2024}\n}\n```\n\n### Citation Style\n\n- Use `\\cite{key}` for parenthetical: \"...as shown previously (Author et al., 2024)\"\n- Use `\\citet{key}` for textual: \"Author et al. (2024) showed that...\"\n\n## Lab Style Conventions\n\n### Quick Reference\n\nThese are the key conventions from our lab's writing style. See `templates/paper_writing/lab_style_guide.md` for complete documentation.\n\n**Language:**\n- Active voice: \"We propose\", \"We examine\", \"We focus on\"\n- Clear and simple - prefer plain language over jargon\n- Bold questions as organizers: `{\\bf what is hypothesis generation?}`\n- Specific quantitative claims: \"8.97% over baselines\"\n\n**Structure:**\n- Modular `commands/` directory with `math.tex`, `general.tex`, `macros.tex`\n- Import with `\\input{commands/math}` etc.\n\n**Macros:**\n- Vectors: `\\va`, `\\vb`, ..., `\\vz` (bold lowercase)\n- Matrices: `\\mA`, `\\mB`, ..., `\\mZ` (bold uppercase)\n- References: `\\figref{}`, `\\Figref{}`, `\\secref{}` (not raw `\\ref{}`)\n- Method names: `\\newcommand{\\methodname}{\\textsc{Name}\\xspace}`\n\n**Tables:**\n- Always use `booktabs` (`\\toprule`, `\\midrule`, `\\bottomrule`)\n- Use `\\resizebox{\\textwidth}{!}{...}` for wide tables\n- Use `@{}` at edges, `\\cmidrule(lr){x-y}` for sub-headers\n- Bold best results\n\n**Hyperlinks (Required):**\n- Always use `\\usepackage[hidelinks]{hyperref}`\n- All citations, refs must be clickable\n\n**Figures:**\n- Use `0.32\\textwidth` for 3-column subfigures\n- Use `\\input{figures/legend}` for shared legends\n- Self-contained captions\n\n**Contribution Lists:**\n```latex\n\\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=0pt,topsep=0pt]\n    \\item We propose...\n    \\item We conduct...\n\\end{itemize}\n```\n\n## Output\n\nSave to `paper_draft/` directory with this structure:\n```\npaper_draft/\n├── main.tex              # Main document\n├── references.bib        # BibTeX citations\n├── commands/\n│   ├── math.tex          # Math notation macros\n│   ├── general.tex       # Formatting macros\n│   └── macros.tex        # Project-specific terms\n├── sections/\n│   ├── abstract.tex\n│   ├── introduction.tex\n│   └── ...\n├── figures/              # Figure files (PDF preferred)\n└── tables/               # Complex standalone tables\n```\n\nCompile with:\n```bash\ncd paper_draft && pdflatex main && bibtex main && pdflatex main && pdflatex main\n```\n\n## Quality Checklist\n\n### Content\n- [ ] Title reflects main contribution\n- [ ] Abstract is self-contained (no citations, no undefined terms)\n- [ ] Contributions clearly stated in introduction\n- [ ] All claims supported by evidence\n- [ ] Limitations honestly discussed\n- [ ] Related work positions paper clearly\n\n### Technical\n- [ ] Method reproducible from description\n- [ ] All experimental details provided\n- [ ] Statistical significance reported\n- [ ] Ablations validate design choices\n\n### Presentation\n- [ ] Figures have informative captions\n- [ ] Tables are properly formatted\n- [ ] All citations present and correct\n- [ ] No placeholder text\n- [ ] Consistent notation throughout\n- [ ] Proofread for typos\n\n### Ethics\n- [ ] Broader impact considered\n- [ ] Potential negative uses discussed\n- [ ] Data/model limitations noted\n\n## References\n\nSee `references/` folder for:\n- `writing_guidelines.md`: Section-specific writing advice\n\nSee `assets/` folder for:\n- `paper_outline_template.md`: Template for Stage 1 outline\n","numLines":355,"startLine":1,"totalLines":355}}}
