{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QuCspBU56bhoMbMscKyKGj","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Lab Writing Style Guide\n2\t\n3\tThis guide documents our lab's conventions for writing academic papers. Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency across all papers.\n4\t\n5\t---\n6\t\n7\t## 1. Language Style\n8\t\n9\t### 1.1 Introduction Structure\n10\t\n11\tFollow this structure for introductions:\n12\t\n13\t1. **Engaging hook** (1-2 paragraphs)\n14\t   - Open with a clear statement about why the problem matters\n15\t   - Get to the point quickly - avoid lengthy build-ups\n16\t\n17\t2. **Problem importance** (1 paragraph)\n18\t   - Establish the significance of the research area\n19\t   - Use specific language: \"Given the ability of LLMs to...\", \"There is growing interest in...\"\n20\t\n21\t3. **Gap identification** (1-2 paragraphs)\n22\t   - Identify what's missing in existing work\n23\t   - Be specific about limitations: \"However, it also becomes increasingly challenging to...\"\n24\t   - Use contrasting structures: \"On one hand... On the other hand...\"\n25\t\n26\t4. **Your approach** (1-2 paragraphs)\n27\t   - Introduce your solution clearly\n28\t   - Use confident language: \"We propose...\", \"We hypothesize that...\"\n29\t   - Reference your method figure: \"(see \\cref{fig:method})\"\n30\t\n31\t5. **Quantitative preview** (1 paragraph)\n32\t   - Include specific numbers: \"8.97% over few-shot, 15.75% over literature-based alone\"\n33\t   - Mention key findings concisely\n34\t\n35\t6. **Contribution bullets** (bulleted list)\n36\t   - 3-4 specific contributions\n37\t   - Start each with an action verb: \"We propose...\", \"We conduct...\", \"We complement...\"\n38\t   - Use tight spacing (see LaTeX section)\n39\t\n40\t### 1.2 Writing Voice\n41\t\n42\t**DO:**\n43\t- Use active voice: \"We propose\", \"We examine\", \"We focus on\"\n44\t- Be direct and confident: \"Our main question is...\", \"We hypothesize that...\"\n45\t- State things clearly and simply - prefer plain language over jargon\n46\t- Use bold questions as organizers: `{\\bf what is hypothesis generation?}`\n47\t- Include specific quantitative claims throughout\n48\t- Use contrasting structures: \"Unlike X, we...\", \"Building on X, we...\"\n49\t\n50\t**DON'T:**\n51\t- Use passive voice excessively: \"It was shown that...\" → \"We show that...\"\n52\t- Be vague: \"good results\" → \"8.97% improvement over baselines\"\n53\t- Use hedging language excessively: \"might possibly\" → \"can\"\n54\t- Use jargon or fancy wording when simple words work: \"utilize\" → \"use\", \"facilitate\" → \"help\"\n55\t- Overcomplicate sentences - if a sentence is hard to parse, simplify it\n56\t\n57\t### 1.3 Hyperlinks\n58\t\n59\t**Always use `hyperref` package** so readers can click on:\n60\t- Citations\n61\t- Section references\n62\t- Figure references\n63\t- Table references\n64\t- URLs\n65\t\n66\t```latex\n67\t\\usepackage[hidelinks]{hyperref}  % hidelinks removes colored boxes\n68\t% or with colored links:\n69\t\\usepackage{hyperref}\n70\t\\hypersetup{colorlinks=true, linkcolor=blue, citecolor=blue, urlcolor=blue}\n71\t```\n72\t\n73\t### 1.4 Section-Specific Guidelines\n74\t\n75\t**Related Work:**\n76\t- Organize by theme (preferred), not chronologically\n77\t- Use positioning phrases: \"Unlike X, we...\", \"Building on X, we...\"\n78\t- End each paragraph by relating back to your work\n79\t\n80\t**Method:**\n81\t- Start with problem formulation\n82\t- Include algorithm pseudocode for complex methods\n83\t- Justify design choices: \"We choose X because...\"\n84\t- Reference implementation details in appendix\n85\t\n86\t**Experiments:**\n87\t- Structure: Setup → Main Results → Analysis → Ablations\n88\t- Include statistical significance (confidence intervals or p-values)\n89\t- Bold best results in tables\n90\t- Explain what the numbers mean, not just report them\n91\t\n92\t**Discussion/Limitations:**\n93\t- Be honest and specific about limitations\n94\t- Discuss failure cases\n95\t- Connect to broader implications\n96\t\n97\t---\n98\t\n99\t## 2. LaTeX Structure\n100\t\n101\t### 2.1 Directory Organization\n102\t\n103\t```\n104\tpaper_draft/\n105\t├── main.tex              # Main file with document class and imports\n106\t├── references.bib        # BibTeX bibliography\n107\t├── commands/\n108\t│   ├── math.tex          # Math notation macros\n109\t│   ├── general.tex       # General formatting macros\n110\t│   └── macros.tex        # Project-specific terms\n111\t├── sections/\n112\t│   ├── abstract.tex\n113\t│   ├── introduction.tex\n114\t│   ├── related_work.tex\n115\t│   ├── methodology.tex\n116\t│   ├── results.tex\n117\t│   ├── discussion.tex\n118\t│   └── conclusion.tex\n119\t├── figures/              # Figure files and .tex for complex figures\n120\t├── tables/               # Complex standalone tables\n121\t└── appendix/             # Appendix sections\n122\t```\n123\t\n124\t### 2.2 Main.tex Structure\n125\t\n126\t```latex\n127\t\\documentclass[final]{neurips_2025}  % or appropriate style\n128\t\n129\t% Standard packages\n130\t\\usepackage{times}\n131\t\\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}\n132\t\\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}\n133\t\\usepackage[hidelinks]{hyperref}\n134\t\\usepackage{natbib}\n135\t\\usepackage{booktabs}\n136\t\\usepackage{graphicx}\n137\t\\usepackage{subcaption}\n138\t\\usepackage{amsmath,amsfonts}\n139\t\\usepackage{xspace}\n140\t\\usepackage{enumitem}\n141\t\n142\t% Import command files\n143\t\\input{commands/math}\n144\t\\input{commands/general}\n145\t\\input{commands/macros}\n146\t\n147\t% Spacing configuration\n148\t\\captionsetup[subfigure]{aboveskip=4pt,belowskip=4pt}\n149\t\\captionsetup[table]{aboveskip=4pt,belowskip=4pt}\n150\t\\captionsetup[figure]{aboveskip=4pt,belowskip=4pt}\n151\t\n152\t\\title{Your Paper Title}\n153\t\\author{...}\n154\t\n155\t\\begin{document}\n156\t\\maketitle\n157\t\n158\t\\begin{abstract}\n159\t\\input{sections/abstract}\n160\t\\end{abstract}\n161\t\n162\t\\input{sections/introduction}\n163\t\\input{sections/related_work}\n164\t\\input{sections/methodology}\n165\t\\input{sections/results}\n166\t\\input{sections/discussion}\n167\t\\input{sections/conclusion}\n168\t\n169\t\\bibliography{references}\n170\t\\end{document}\n171\t```\n172\t\n173\t---\n174\t\n175\t## 3. Math Notation\n176\t\n177\t### 3.1 Notation Conventions\n178\t\n179\t| Type | Convention | Example |\n180\t|------|------------|---------|\n181\t| Vectors | Bold lowercase | `\\va`, `\\vb`, `\\vx` → **a**, **b**, **x** |\n182\t| Matrices | Bold uppercase | `\\mA`, `\\mB`, `\\mX` → **A**, **B**, **X** |\n183\t| Calligraphic | mathcal | `\\gA`, `\\gD`, `\\gL` → 𝒜, 𝒟, ℒ |\n184\t| Sets | Blackboard bold | `\\sR`, `\\sN`, `\\sZ` → ℝ, ℕ, ℤ |\n185\t| Operators | DeclareMathOperator | `\\argmax`, `\\argmin` |\n186\t\n187\t### 3.2 Common Macros\n188\t\n189\t```latex\n190\t\\E           % Expectation: 𝔼\n191\t\\R           % Real numbers: ℝ\n192\t\\argmax      % arg max\n193\t\\argmin      % arg min\n194\t\\train       % Training set: 𝒟\n195\t\\test        % Test set: 𝒟_test\n196\t```\n197\t\n198\t---\n199\t\n200\t## 4. Reference Macros\n201\t\n202\t### 4.1 Figure References\n203\t\n204\t```latex\n205\t\\figref{fig:method}      % \"figure 1\" (lowercase, mid-sentence)\n206\t\\Figref{fig:method}      % \"Figure 1\" (capitalized, start of sentence)\n207\t\\twofigref{fig:a}{fig:b} % \"figures 1 and 2\"\n208\t```\n209\t\n210\t### 4.2 Section References\n211\t\n212\t```latex\n213\t\\secref{sec:method}      % \"section 3\"\n214\t\\Secref{sec:method}      % \"Section 3\"\n215\t```\n216\t\n217\t### 4.3 Using cleveref\n218\t\n219\tFor more sophisticated references, use the `cleveref` package:\n220\t\n221\t```latex\n222\t\\usepackage[noabbrev,capitalize]{cleveref}\n223\t\\crefname{section}{\\S}{\\S\\S}\n224\t\n225\t% Usage:\n226\t\\cref{fig:method}        % Auto-formatted based on reference type\n227\t\\cref{sec:intro,sec:method}  % \"Sections 1 and 3\"\n228\t```\n229\t\n230\t---\n231\t\n232\t## 5. Table Formatting\n233\t\n234\t### 5.1 Basic Structure\n235\t\n236\t```latex\n237\t\\begin{table}[t]\n238\t    \\centering\n239\t    \\resizebox{\\textwidth}{!}{%\n240\t    \\begin{tabular}{@{}llccc@{}}\n241\t        \\toprule\n242\t        \\textbf{Method} & \\textbf{Dataset} & \\textbf{Acc} & \\textbf{F1} \\\\\n243\t        \\midrule\n244\t        Baseline & Dataset-A & 75.2 & 72.1 \\\\\n245\t        \\textbf{Ours} & Dataset-A & \\textbf{82.1} & \\textbf{79.4} \\\\\n246\t        \\bottomrule\n247\t    \\end{tabular}\n248\t    }\n249\t    \\caption{Results on Dataset-A. Best results in \\textbf{bold}.}\n250\t    \\label{tab:results}\n251\t\\end{table}\n252\t```\n253\t\n254\t### 5.2 Key Conventions\n255\t\n256\t- **Always use `booktabs`**: `\\toprule`, `\\midrule`, `\\bottomrule`\n257\t- **No vertical lines**: Never use `|` in column specs\n258\t- **Remove edge padding**: Use `@{}` at table edges\n259\t- **Use `\\resizebox`**: `\\resizebox{\\textwidth}{!}{...}` for wide tables\n260\t- **Sub-headers**: Use `\\cmidrule(lr){2-4}` for grouping columns\n261\t- **Row spacing**: `\\renewcommand{\\arraystretch}{1.25}` for readability\n262\t- **Text columns**: Use `p{Xcm}` for wrapped text\n263\t- **Bold best results**: Highlight best numbers with `\\textbf{}`\n264\t- **Dataset/method names**: Use `\\textsc{}` in headers\n265\t\n266\t### 5.3 Multi-column Headers\n267\t\n268\t```latex\n269\t\\begin{tabular}{lcccccc}\n270\t    \\toprule\n271\t    \\multirow{2}{*}{Method} & \\multicolumn{2}{c}{GPT} & \\multicolumn{2}{c}{Llama} \\\\\n272\t    \\cmidrule(lr){2-3} \\cmidrule(lr){4-5}\n273\t    & Acc & F1 & Acc & F1 \\\\\n274\t    \\midrule\n275\t    ...\n276\t\\end{tabular}\n277\t```\n278\t\n279\t---\n280\t\n281\t## 6. Figure Formatting\n282\t\n283\t### 6.1 Single Figure\n284\t\n285\t```latex\n286\t\\begin{figure}[t]\n287\t    \\centering\n288\t    \\includegraphics[width=0.95\\linewidth]{figures/method.pdf}\n289\t    \\caption{Overview of our method. We first... then... finally...}\n290\t    \\label{fig:method}\n291\t\\end{figure}\n292\t```\n293\t\n294\t### 6.2 Multi-panel Subfigures (3-column)\n295\t\n296\t```latex\n297\t\\begin{figure}[t]\n298\t    \\centering\n299\t    \\begin{subfigure}[b]{0.32\\textwidth}\n300\t        \\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{figures/plot_a.pdf}\n301\t        \\caption{Metric A}\n302\t        \\label{fig:plot_a}\n303\t    \\end{subfigure}\n304\t    \\begin{subfigure}[b]{0.32\\textwidth}\n305\t        \\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{figures/plot_b.pdf}\n306\t        \\caption{Metric B}\n307\t        \\label{fig:plot_b}\n308\t    \\end{subfigure}\n309\t    \\begin{subfigure}[b]{0.32\\textwidth}\n310\t        \\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{figures/plot_c.pdf}\n311\t        \\caption{Metric C}\n312\t        \\label{fig:plot_c}\n313\t    \\end{subfigure}\n314\t    \\input{figures/legend}  % Shared legend\n315\t    \\caption{Results across three metrics. \\figleft shows...}\n316\t    \\label{fig:results}\n317\t\\end{figure}\n318\t```\n319\t\n320\t### 6.3 Caption Conventions\n321\t\n322\t- Captions should be self-contained\n323\t- Explain what is shown\n324\t- Highlight key observations\n325\t- Use `\\figleft`, `\\figright`, `\\captiona`, `\\captionb` for sub-panel references\n326\t\n327\t---\n328\t\n329\t## 7. Results Presentation\n330\t\n331\t### 7.1 Colored Arrows\n332\t\n333\t```latex\n334\t% In tables or text, show improvement/decline\n335\tOur method achieves 82.1\\% \\increase compared to 75.2\\% for baseline \\decrease\n336\t```\n337\t\n338\t### 7.2 Contribution Lists\n339\t\n340\t```latex\n341\t\\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=0pt,topsep=0pt]\n342\t    \\item We propose a novel framework for...\n343\t    \\item We conduct comprehensive experiments on...\n344\t    \\item We release our code and data at...\n345\t\\end{itemize}\n346\t```\n347\t\n348\t---\n349\t\n350\t## 8. Algorithm Styling\n351\t\n352\t### 8.1 Basic Algorithm\n353\t\n354\t```latex\n355\t\\usepackage{algorithm}\n356\t\\usepackage[noend]{algpseudocode}\n357\t\n358\t\\begin{algorithm}[t]\n359\t\\caption{Our Method}\n360\t\\label{alg:method}\n361\t\\begin{algorithmic}[1]\n362\t\\INPUT Data $\\gD$, model $\\gM$\n363\t\\OUTPUT Hypotheses $\\gH$\n364\t\\State Initialize $\\gH \\gets \\emptyset$\n365\t\\For{each example $x \\in \\gD$}\n366\t    \\State $h \\gets \\gM(x)$ \\Comment{Generate hypothesis}\n367\t    \\State $\\gH \\gets \\gH \\cup \\{h\\}$\n368\t\\EndFor\n369\t\\State \\Return $\\gH$\n370\t\\end{algorithmic}\n371\t\\end{algorithm}\n372\t```\n373\t\n374\t### 8.2 Comment Style\n375\t\n376\tUse `\\triangleright` for inline comments:\n377\t```latex\n378\t\\newcommand{\\rightcomment}[1]{\\(\\triangleright\\) {\\small \\it #1}}\n379\t```\n380\t\n381\t---\n382\t\n383\t## 9. Citations\n384\t\n385\t### 9.1 Citation Styles\n386\t\n387\t```latex\n388\t\\cite{author2024}        % Parenthetical: (Author et al., 2024)\n389\t\\citet{author2024}       % Textual: Author et al. (2024)\n390\t\\cite[e.g.,][]{key}      % With prefix: (e.g., Author et al., 2024)\n391\t```\n392\t\n393\t### 9.2 BibTeX Entry Format\n394\t\n395\t```bibtex\n396\t@inproceedings{zhou2024hypogenic,\n397\t    title={Hypothesis Generation with Large Language Models},\n398\t    author={Zhou, Yangqiaoyu and Liu, Haokun and Srivastava, Tejes and Mei, Hongyuan and Tan, Chenhao},\n399\t    booktitle={Proceedings of ACL},\n400\t    year={2024}\n401\t}\n402\t```\n403\t\n404\t---\n405\t\n406\t## 10. Quick Reference Checklist\n407\t\n408\tBefore submitting, verify:\n409\t\n410\t- [ ] Active voice used throughout\n411\t- [ ] Specific quantitative claims in introduction\n412\t- [ ] Contributions listed with action verbs\n413\t- [ ] All tables use `booktabs` (no vertical lines)\n414\t- [ ] Best results bolded in tables\n415\t- [ ] Figures have self-contained captions\n416\t- [ ] References use `\\figref`, `\\secref` macros\n417\t- [ ] Method/dataset names use `\\textsc` with `\\xspace`\n418\t- [ ] Commands directory properly imported\n419\t- [ ] No placeholder text remaining\n420\t- [ ] Paper compiles without errors\n421\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"6fbcd0a4-5ad7-4447-9fee-7a7864e1073f","uuid":"37da37d8-6a3e-4238-8329-3dc4ff8ea347","timestamp":"2026-07-03T10:17:10.583Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/workspaces/predicting_lichess_chess_puzzl_20260702_184615_ee687164/templates/paper_writing/lab_style_guide.md","content":"# Lab Writing Style Guide\n\nThis guide documents our lab's conventions for writing academic papers. Follow these guidelines to ensure consistency across all papers.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Language Style\n\n### 1.1 Introduction Structure\n\nFollow this structure for introductions:\n\n1. **Engaging hook** (1-2 paragraphs)\n   - Open with a clear statement about why the problem matters\n   - Get to the point quickly - avoid lengthy build-ups\n\n2. **Problem importance** (1 paragraph)\n   - Establish the significance of the research area\n   - Use specific language: \"Given the ability of LLMs to...\", \"There is growing interest in...\"\n\n3. **Gap identification** (1-2 paragraphs)\n   - Identify what's missing in existing work\n   - Be specific about limitations: \"However, it also becomes increasingly challenging to...\"\n   - Use contrasting structures: \"On one hand... On the other hand...\"\n\n4. **Your approach** (1-2 paragraphs)\n   - Introduce your solution clearly\n   - Use confident language: \"We propose...\", \"We hypothesize that...\"\n   - Reference your method figure: \"(see \\cref{fig:method})\"\n\n5. **Quantitative preview** (1 paragraph)\n   - Include specific numbers: \"8.97% over few-shot, 15.75% over literature-based alone\"\n   - Mention key findings concisely\n\n6. **Contribution bullets** (bulleted list)\n   - 3-4 specific contributions\n   - Start each with an action verb: \"We propose...\", \"We conduct...\", \"We complement...\"\n   - Use tight spacing (see LaTeX section)\n\n### 1.2 Writing Voice\n\n**DO:**\n- Use active voice: \"We propose\", \"We examine\", \"We focus on\"\n- Be direct and confident: \"Our main question is...\", \"We hypothesize that...\"\n- State things clearly and simply - prefer plain language over jargon\n- Use bold questions as organizers: `{\\bf what is hypothesis generation?}`\n- Include specific quantitative claims throughout\n- Use contrasting structures: \"Unlike X, we...\", \"Building on X, we...\"\n\n**DON'T:**\n- Use passive voice excessively: \"It was shown that...\" → \"We show that...\"\n- Be vague: \"good results\" → \"8.97% improvement over baselines\"\n- Use hedging language excessively: \"might possibly\" → \"can\"\n- Use jargon or fancy wording when simple words work: \"utilize\" → \"use\", \"facilitate\" → \"help\"\n- Overcomplicate sentences - if a sentence is hard to parse, simplify it\n\n### 1.3 Hyperlinks\n\n**Always use `hyperref` package** so readers can click on:\n- Citations\n- Section references\n- Figure references\n- Table references\n- URLs\n\n```latex\n\\usepackage[hidelinks]{hyperref}  % hidelinks removes colored boxes\n% or with colored links:\n\\usepackage{hyperref}\n\\hypersetup{colorlinks=true, linkcolor=blue, citecolor=blue, urlcolor=blue}\n```\n\n### 1.4 Section-Specific Guidelines\n\n**Related Work:**\n- Organize by theme (preferred), not chronologically\n- Use positioning phrases: \"Unlike X, we...\", \"Building on X, we...\"\n- End each paragraph by relating back to your work\n\n**Method:**\n- Start with problem formulation\n- Include algorithm pseudocode for complex methods\n- Justify design choices: \"We choose X because...\"\n- Reference implementation details in appendix\n\n**Experiments:**\n- Structure: Setup → Main Results → Analysis → Ablations\n- Include statistical significance (confidence intervals or p-values)\n- Bold best results in tables\n- Explain what the numbers mean, not just report them\n\n**Discussion/Limitations:**\n- Be honest and specific about limitations\n- Discuss failure cases\n- Connect to broader implications\n\n---\n\n## 2. LaTeX Structure\n\n### 2.1 Directory Organization\n\n```\npaper_draft/\n├── main.tex              # Main file with document class and imports\n├── references.bib        # BibTeX bibliography\n├── commands/\n│   ├── math.tex          # Math notation macros\n│   ├── general.tex       # General formatting macros\n│   └── macros.tex        # Project-specific terms\n├── sections/\n│   ├── abstract.tex\n│   ├── introduction.tex\n│   ├── related_work.tex\n│   ├── methodology.tex\n│   ├── results.tex\n│   ├── discussion.tex\n│   └── conclusion.tex\n├── figures/              # Figure files and .tex for complex figures\n├── tables/               # Complex standalone tables\n└── appendix/             # Appendix sections\n```\n\n### 2.2 Main.tex Structure\n\n```latex\n\\documentclass[final]{neurips_2025}  % or appropriate style\n\n% Standard packages\n\\usepackage{times}\n\\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}\n\\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}\n\\usepackage[hidelinks]{hyperref}\n\\usepackage{natbib}\n\\usepackage{booktabs}\n\\usepackage{graphicx}\n\\usepackage{subcaption}\n\\usepackage{amsmath,amsfonts}\n\\usepackage{xspace}\n\\usepackage{enumitem}\n\n% Import command files\n\\input{commands/math}\n\\input{commands/general}\n\\input{commands/macros}\n\n% Spacing configuration\n\\captionsetup[subfigure]{aboveskip=4pt,belowskip=4pt}\n\\captionsetup[table]{aboveskip=4pt,belowskip=4pt}\n\\captionsetup[figure]{aboveskip=4pt,belowskip=4pt}\n\n\\title{Your Paper Title}\n\\author{...}\n\n\\begin{document}\n\\maketitle\n\n\\begin{abstract}\n\\input{sections/abstract}\n\\end{abstract}\n\n\\input{sections/introduction}\n\\input{sections/related_work}\n\\input{sections/methodology}\n\\input{sections/results}\n\\input{sections/discussion}\n\\input{sections/conclusion}\n\n\\bibliography{references}\n\\end{document}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 3. Math Notation\n\n### 3.1 Notation Conventions\n\n| Type | Convention | Example |\n|------|------------|---------|\n| Vectors | Bold lowercase | `\\va`, `\\vb`, `\\vx` → **a**, **b**, **x** |\n| Matrices | Bold uppercase | `\\mA`, `\\mB`, `\\mX` → **A**, **B**, **X** |\n| Calligraphic | mathcal | `\\gA`, `\\gD`, `\\gL` → 𝒜, 𝒟, ℒ |\n| Sets | Blackboard bold | `\\sR`, `\\sN`, `\\sZ` → ℝ, ℕ, ℤ |\n| Operators | DeclareMathOperator | `\\argmax`, `\\argmin` |\n\n### 3.2 Common Macros\n\n```latex\n\\E           % Expectation: 𝔼\n\\R           % Real numbers: ℝ\n\\argmax      % arg max\n\\argmin      % arg min\n\\train       % Training set: 𝒟\n\\test        % Test set: 𝒟_test\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Reference Macros\n\n### 4.1 Figure References\n\n```latex\n\\figref{fig:method}      % \"figure 1\" (lowercase, mid-sentence)\n\\Figref{fig:method}      % \"Figure 1\" (capitalized, start of sentence)\n\\twofigref{fig:a}{fig:b} % \"figures 1 and 2\"\n```\n\n### 4.2 Section References\n\n```latex\n\\secref{sec:method}      % \"section 3\"\n\\Secref{sec:method}      % \"Section 3\"\n```\n\n### 4.3 Using cleveref\n\nFor more sophisticated references, use the `cleveref` package:\n\n```latex\n\\usepackage[noabbrev,capitalize]{cleveref}\n\\crefname{section}{\\S}{\\S\\S}\n\n% Usage:\n\\cref{fig:method}        % Auto-formatted based on reference type\n\\cref{sec:intro,sec:method}  % \"Sections 1 and 3\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Table Formatting\n\n### 5.1 Basic Structure\n\n```latex\n\\begin{table}[t]\n    \\centering\n    \\resizebox{\\textwidth}{!}{%\n    \\begin{tabular}{@{}llccc@{}}\n        \\toprule\n        \\textbf{Method} & \\textbf{Dataset} & \\textbf{Acc} & \\textbf{F1} \\\\\n        \\midrule\n        Baseline & Dataset-A & 75.2 & 72.1 \\\\\n        \\textbf{Ours} & Dataset-A & \\textbf{82.1} & \\textbf{79.4} \\\\\n        \\bottomrule\n    \\end{tabular}\n    }\n    \\caption{Results on Dataset-A. Best results in \\textbf{bold}.}\n    \\label{tab:results}\n\\end{table}\n```\n\n### 5.2 Key Conventions\n\n- **Always use `booktabs`**: `\\toprule`, `\\midrule`, `\\bottomrule`\n- **No vertical lines**: Never use `|` in column specs\n- **Remove edge padding**: Use `@{}` at table edges\n- **Use `\\resizebox`**: `\\resizebox{\\textwidth}{!}{...}` for wide tables\n- **Sub-headers**: Use `\\cmidrule(lr){2-4}` for grouping columns\n- **Row spacing**: `\\renewcommand{\\arraystretch}{1.25}` for readability\n- **Text columns**: Use `p{Xcm}` for wrapped text\n- **Bold best results**: Highlight best numbers with `\\textbf{}`\n- **Dataset/method names**: Use `\\textsc{}` in headers\n\n### 5.3 Multi-column Headers\n\n```latex\n\\begin{tabular}{lcccccc}\n    \\toprule\n    \\multirow{2}{*}{Method} & \\multicolumn{2}{c}{GPT} & \\multicolumn{2}{c}{Llama} \\\\\n    \\cmidrule(lr){2-3} \\cmidrule(lr){4-5}\n    & Acc & F1 & Acc & F1 \\\\\n    \\midrule\n    ...\n\\end{tabular}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Figure Formatting\n\n### 6.1 Single Figure\n\n```latex\n\\begin{figure}[t]\n    \\centering\n    \\includegraphics[width=0.95\\linewidth]{figures/method.pdf}\n    \\caption{Overview of our method. We first... then... finally...}\n    \\label{fig:method}\n\\end{figure}\n```\n\n### 6.2 Multi-panel Subfigures (3-column)\n\n```latex\n\\begin{figure}[t]\n    \\centering\n    \\begin{subfigure}[b]{0.32\\textwidth}\n        \\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{figures/plot_a.pdf}\n        \\caption{Metric A}\n        \\label{fig:plot_a}\n    \\end{subfigure}\n    \\begin{subfigure}[b]{0.32\\textwidth}\n        \\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{figures/plot_b.pdf}\n        \\caption{Metric B}\n        \\label{fig:plot_b}\n    \\end{subfigure}\n    \\begin{subfigure}[b]{0.32\\textwidth}\n        \\includegraphics[width=\\textwidth]{figures/plot_c.pdf}\n        \\caption{Metric C}\n        \\label{fig:plot_c}\n    \\end{subfigure}\n    \\input{figures/legend}  % Shared legend\n    \\caption{Results across three metrics. \\figleft shows...}\n    \\label{fig:results}\n\\end{figure}\n```\n\n### 6.3 Caption Conventions\n\n- Captions should be self-contained\n- Explain what is shown\n- Highlight key observations\n- Use `\\figleft`, `\\figright`, `\\captiona`, `\\captionb` for sub-panel references\n\n---\n\n## 7. Results Presentation\n\n### 7.1 Colored Arrows\n\n```latex\n% In tables or text, show improvement/decline\nOur method achieves 82.1\\% \\increase compared to 75.2\\% for baseline \\decrease\n```\n\n### 7.2 Contribution Lists\n\n```latex\n\\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=*,itemsep=0pt,topsep=0pt]\n    \\item We propose a novel framework for...\n    \\item We conduct comprehensive experiments on...\n    \\item We release our code and data at...\n\\end{itemize}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 8. Algorithm Styling\n\n### 8.1 Basic Algorithm\n\n```latex\n\\usepackage{algorithm}\n\\usepackage[noend]{algpseudocode}\n\n\\begin{algorithm}[t]\n\\caption{Our Method}\n\\label{alg:method}\n\\begin{algorithmic}[1]\n\\INPUT Data $\\gD$, model $\\gM$\n\\OUTPUT Hypotheses $\\gH$\n\\State Initialize $\\gH \\gets \\emptyset$\n\\For{each example $x \\in \\gD$}\n    \\State $h \\gets \\gM(x)$ \\Comment{Generate hypothesis}\n    \\State $\\gH \\gets \\gH \\cup \\{h\\}$\n\\EndFor\n\\State \\Return $\\gH$\n\\end{algorithmic}\n\\end{algorithm}\n```\n\n### 8.2 Comment Style\n\nUse `\\triangleright` for inline comments:\n```latex\n\\newcommand{\\rightcomment}[1]{\\(\\triangleright\\) {\\small \\it #1}}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 9. Citations\n\n### 9.1 Citation Styles\n\n```latex\n\\cite{author2024}        % Parenthetical: (Author et al., 2024)\n\\citet{author2024}       % Textual: Author et al. (2024)\n\\cite[e.g.,][]{key}      % With prefix: (e.g., Author et al., 2024)\n```\n\n### 9.2 BibTeX Entry Format\n\n```bibtex\n@inproceedings{zhou2024hypogenic,\n    title={Hypothesis Generation with Large Language Models},\n    author={Zhou, Yangqiaoyu and Liu, Haokun and Srivastava, Tejes and Mei, Hongyuan and Tan, Chenhao},\n    booktitle={Proceedings of ACL},\n    year={2024}\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 10. Quick Reference Checklist\n\nBefore submitting, verify:\n\n- [ ] Active voice used throughout\n- [ ] Specific quantitative claims in introduction\n- [ ] Contributions listed with action verbs\n- [ ] All tables use `booktabs` (no vertical lines)\n- [ ] Best results bolded in tables\n- [ ] Figures have self-contained captions\n- [ ] References use `\\figref`, `\\secref` macros\n- [ ] Method/dataset names use `\\textsc` with `\\xspace`\n- [ ] Commands directory properly imported\n- [ ] No placeholder text remaining\n- [ ] Paper compiles without errors\n","numLines":421,"startLine":1,"totalLines":421}}}
